properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT COROWA 

Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Corowa where the river level is approaching its peak.   
   
Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal: 
Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Corowa.   
The Murray River at Corowa is currently at 4.84 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Murray River at Corowa is likely to peak near 4.90 metres Monday afternoon, with minor flooding.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 11/07/2023 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham.
  • Minor flooding continues along the Murray River at Barham where moderate flooding is possible from Tuesday. 
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.73 metres and rising slowly, above the minor flood level (5.50 metres). 
  • The Murray River at Barham may reach the moderate flood level (5.80 metres) during Tuesday. 
  • This is considerably lower than the peak of 6.21 m in November 2022. 
  • The peak forecast at Barham will be provided once upstream peaks have been observed. 
  • River levels at Torrumbarry Weir are rising slowly and may approach the minor flood level from Tuesday. 
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir is currently at 7.22 metres (below the minor flood level of 7.30 metres) and rising slowly. 
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may reach the minor flood level (7.30 metres) (37,200 ML/d) during Tuesday. 
  • This is considerably lower than the peak level of 7.84 m, and the peak flow of 56,000ML/d in October 2022. 
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

Impacts in your area:
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services. 
  • Check the Parks Victoria website (https://www.parks.vic.gov.au/get-into-nature/safety-in-nature/changed-conditions-and-closures) for park closures. 
  • This flood will likely be contained within the forested areas.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 11/07/2023 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.92 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 metres) for the next few days.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

  • Due to a whale carcass that remains on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on 23 June.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 13/07/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility:

ADVICE - DANGEROUS ANIMAL - Avoid the Area
Incident Location: Point Ricardo
Issue Date: Friday 07 July 2023, 12:31 pm
Next Update: Thursday 13 July 2023, 12:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/29695/moreinfo

This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

- Due to a whale carcass that remains on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo. 
- A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
- While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area. 
- This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on 23 June.


Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River at Wangaratta.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT WANGARATTA

Recent rainfall across the King River catchment has caused near moderate flooding along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge where the river level peaked just below the moderate flood level (3.95 metres).

Minor flooding is occurring at Wangaratta where it is likely to reach 12.20 metres Monday evening and cause flooding in the Caravan Park. The river level may peak near 12.30 metres overnight Monday into Tuesday.

In the 24 hours to 4:00 pm Monday, rainfall totals of up to 10 mm have been recorded across the Ovens and King River catchments. 

Showers are forecast for the next few days. River levels are likely to remain elevated for the next few days.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.
The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 12.16 metres and rising slowly with minor flooding. The Ovens River at Wangaratta is likely to reach around 12.20 metres Monday evening and may peak near 12.30 metres overnight Monday into Tuesday, with minor flooding.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Yogi is possibly going to get wet and should have a life jacket on.
  • Water flows across Apex Park and enters lagoon behind Painters Island Caravan Park.
  • Overtopping of Ovens River in Frank Garth Reserve upstream of flood way bridge may commences.
  • Water commences to pass beneath floodway span of Parfitt Road Bridge upstream of Apex Park.
  • Bickerton Street carpark overtops after depressions in Apex Park fill resulting in progressive filling of lagoon around Painters Island Caravan Park.
  • Dale Street railway underpass may start to flood.
  • Over-topping of Pinkton Crescent occurs.
  • Overflows drain away toward Dale St and Wills St.
  • Great Alpine Road closed near Wangaratta and the detour road maybe active.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 11/07/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Goulburn River Eildon to Seymour.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE IN THE FLOOD WATCH AREA FROM MONDAY EVENING

A strong cold front has crossed Victoria over the weekend causing showers and isolated thunder storms across the flood watch area.

Catchments in the flood watch area are relatively wet. River and stream levels are already elevated due to recent rainfall, with minor flooding occurring in some catchments.

Rainfall totals of up to 5 mm are forecast across the flood watch area for the remainder of Monday to Tuesday.

Minor flooding is possible within the flood watch area from Monday evening.

Catchments likely to be affected include:
  • Ovens and King Rivers (A minor warning is current for parts of Ovens and King Rivers)
  • Goulburn River Eildon to Seymour

A minor flood warning is current for the Kiewa River catchment.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 11/07/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
